      "content": "In that case, you can use the `heapq` module's stable sorting algorithm, `heapify` and `heappop`, to achieve a more definitive ordering. Here's a revised implementation:\n\n```python\nimport heapq\n\nclass TradeData:\n    def __init__(self, timestamp, volume, price):\n        self.timestamp = timestamp\n        self.volume = volume\n        self.price = price\n\n    def __lt__(self, other):\n        if self.timestamp != other.timestamp:\n            return self.timestamp < other.timestamp\n        elif self.volume != other.volume:\n            return self.volume < other.volume\n        else:\n            return self.price < other.price\n\ndef process_trade_data(data: list[tuple[int, int, float]]) -> list[tuple[int, int, float]]:\n    \"\"\"Sorts trade data by timestamp (int), then by volume (int), then by price (float).\"\"\"\n    \n    # Convert trade data to TradeData objects for easy comparison\n    trade_data_objects = [TradeData(*data[i]) for i in range(len(data))]\n    \n    # Heap sort using the TradeData objects\n    trade_data_objects = heapq.merge(*[trade_data_objects])\n    \n    # Convert the sorted TradeData objects back",
